      <h4>2. <strong>Carbon Monoxide Poisoning:</strong></h4>
      <p>- <strong>Incomplete Combustion:</strong> Gas stoves and ovens can produce carbon monoxide (CO) if they are not
        burning fuel efficiently. Without proper ventilation, CO can build up to dangerous levels, leading to symptoms like
        headaches, dizziness, nausea, and even death in extreme cases.</p>
      <h4>3. <strong>Mold and Mildew Growth:</strong></h4>
      <p>- <strong>Excess Moisture:</strong> Cooking generates steam and moisture, which can lead to high humidity levels in
        the kitchen. This creates an ideal environment for mold and mildew to grow, which can cause respiratory issues,
        allergic reactions, and other health problems.</p>
      <h4>4. <strong>Exposure to Volatile Organic Compounds (VOCs):</strong></h4>
      <p>- <strong>Cooking Oils and Fats:</strong> Heating oils and fats can release VOCs, which are harmful chemicals that
        can cause headaches, dizziness, and long-term health issues like liver and kidney damage.</p>
      <p>- <strong>Cleaning Products:</strong> Many kitchen cleaning products also emit VOCs, and without proper ventilation,
        these chemicals can accumulate in the air.</p>
      <h4>5. <strong>Eye and Skin Irritation:</strong></h4>
      <p>- <strong>Smoke and Grease Particles:</strong> These can irritate the eyes and skin, causing redness, itching, and
        discomfort.</p>
      <h4>6. <strong>Heat Exhaustion:</strong></h4>
      <p>- <strong>Excess Heat:</strong> Without proper ventilation, the kitchen can become excessively hot, leading to heat
        exhaustion, especially for those spending extended periods cooking.</p>
      <h4>7. <strong>Fire Hazard:</strong></h4>
      <p>- <strong>Grease Build-Up:</strong> Improper ventilation can lead to grease accumulation in the range hood and
        ductwork, increasing the risk of a kitchen fire. This is not a direct health risk but poses a significant safety
        threat.</p>
      <h4>8. <strong>Poor Indoor Air Quality:</strong></h4>
      <p>- <strong>Accumulation of Pollutants:</strong> A poorly vented range hood can lead to a buildup of various indoor air
        pollutants, negatively impacting overall indoor air quality and contributing to "sick building syndrome," which
        includes symptoms like headaches, fatigue, and irritation of the eyes, nose, and throat.</p>
      <h4>Preventative Measures:</h4>
      <p>- <strong>Regular Maintenance:</strong> Clean the range hood filters and ductwork regularly to ensure proper airflow.
      </p>
      <p>- <strong>Proper Installation:</strong> Ensure the range hood is correctly installed and vented to the outside, not
        into the attic or another interior space.</p>
      <p>- <strong>Monitor Air Quality:</strong> Consider using an air quality monitor to keep track of pollutant levels in
        your kitchen.</p>
      <p>- <strong>Use Exhaust Fans:</strong> Use additional exhaust fans or open windows to improve ventilation when cooking.
      </p>
      <p>By addressing these issues and ensuring your range hood is properly vented, you can significantly reduce these health
        risks and maintain a safer and healthier kitchen environment.</p>
